answer.en:
### Type-Safe Builder Pattern

The builder pattern with TypeScript can track which properties have been set at the type level. Use a boolean-indexed generic to represent the state of each property, ensuring compile-time verification that all required fields are configured before building.

This approach uses union types and conditional types to make `build()` only callable when all required properties are set. Each setter returns a new builder state with that property marked as true.

```typescript
type Builder<T extends Record<string, any>, R extends Record<string, boolean>> = {
  build(): R extends Record<string, true> ? T : never;
  setName(name: string): Builder<T, R & { name: true }>;
  setAge(age: number): Builder<T, R & { age: true }>;
};

function createBuilder<T>(): Builder<T, {}> {
  const state: any = {};
  return {
    setName(name: string) { return createBuilder(); },
    setAge(age: number) { return createBuilder(); },
    build() { return state; }
  };
}

const builder = createBuilder();
builder.setName('John').setAge(30).build(); // ✓
// builder.build(); // ✗ Type error
```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates implement builders that don't actually track state in the type system, making `build()` callable before all properties are set.

answer.ru:
