### Exhaustiveness Checking with Never

Use a helper function that accepts `never` to force TypeScript to verify all union branches are covered. If a case is missed, the compiler will complain about assigning a value to `never`.

```typescript
type Action = { type: 'save' } | { type: 'delete' };
const assertNever = (x: never): never => { throw new Error(`Unexpected: ${x}`); };
function handle(action: Action) {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'save': console.log('Saving'); break;
    case 'delete': console.log('Deleting'); break;
    default: assertNever(action); // ✗ Error if case missing
  }
}
```

**Common interview trap:** Thinking exhaustiveness checking happens automatically without an explicit `assertNever` guard or that it works with implicit `any` types.

